  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve Chardonnay at different temperatures for different food pairings?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, serving temperature significantly affects pairing success. Serve crisp, unoaked Chardonnays at 45-48°F to maintain their refreshing acidity with light appetizers and raw preparations. Fuller-bodied, oaked Chardonnays benefit from slightly warmer service (50-55°F) to allow their complex flavors to emerge and complement richer main courses. The warmer temperature enhances the wine's texture and aromatic compounds, creating better harmony with substantial dishes.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when pairing Chardonnay with food?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is treating all Chardonnays the same—pairing a delicate Sancerre with heavy cream sauces or matching an oaky Napa Chardonnay with raw oysters. Each style requires different food approaches based on weight, oak treatment, and regional characteristics. Understanding whether you're working with a lean, mineral Chablis or a rich, buttery Sonoma Coast bottling is crucial for successful pairing.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can Chardonnay pair with spicy food, and if so, which styles work best?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Off-dry and unoaked Chardonnays can handle moderate spice levels, particularly in Asian cuisine where their fruit sweetness balances heat while acidity cleanses the palate. Avoid heavily oaked styles with very spicy dishes as the combination of alcohol, oak tannins, and capsaicin creates an unpleasant burning sensation. Alsatian Chardonnays and some Australian examples with residual sugar work particularly well with Thai and Indian dishes with medium spice levels.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Chardonnay food pairing good for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely—Chardonnay is ideal for beginners because it's widely available, food-friendly, and comes in clearly distinct styles that teach fundamental pairing principles. Starting with the contrast between crisp Chablis with oysters versus rich Chardonnay with roasted chicken demonstrates how wine style affects food compatibility. The grape's versatility allows new wine drinkers to experiment safely while learning to identify oak influence, acidity levels, and regional characteristics through food pairing.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the best value Chardonnay regions for food pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Languedoc and Loire Valley in France offer exceptional food-pairing Chardonnays under $20, providing both mineral-driven and lightly oaked styles. Washington State and cool-climate Australian regions like Adelaide Hills deliver outstanding quality-to-price ratios with food-friendly acidity and balanced oak. These regions produce versatile Chardonnays that complement a wide range of dishes without the premium pricing of Burgundy or Napa Valley.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can I keep an opened bottle of Chardonnay for food pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Unoaked Chardonnays maintain their food-pairing qualities for 3-5 days when properly stored with a wine preserver and refrigerated, as their bright acidity preserves freshness. Oaked Chardonnays may last 2-3 days before their complex flavors begin to fade and oxidation affects their ability to complement rich dishes. For optimal food pairing, consume within 48 hours as the wine's balance and aromatic intensity are crucial for successful matches.</p>
